          img(src="img/language_adapters.png" width="60%")
          small Source: Rathnayake et al., Adapter-based fine-tuning of pre-trained multilingual language models for code-mixed and code-switched text classification
        section
          h1 Code-mixing and Language Identification
        section
          h2 Code-mixing, switching
          ul
            li Extremely common in multilingual communities, especially online (3.5% of all tweets)
            li Code-mixing: Matrix language with insertions from other languages (often English)
            li Code-switching: changing between languages
            li Loanwords: words from other languages (understandable to speakers without knowledge of the other language)
        section
          h2 Challenges for code-mixed language
          ul
            li Lack of data; most text is from noisy sources
            li Many combinations of languages
            li How to apply monolingual trained models to code-mixed texts?
        section
          h2 Methods for code-mixed language
          ul
            li Supervised learning (from scratch)
            li Divide-and-conquer
            li Translate to matrix language
            li Zero-shot approach
        section
          h1 Hands-on: Language Identification
        section(data-background-image="img/distant_reading.png" data-background-opacity=0.5)
          h1 Distant Reading
        section
          h2 Close vs Distance Reading
          ul
            li Close reading is the traditional way of reading a text
            li Distant reading uses computational methods to analyse canons of text
            li Term attributed to Franco Moretti (2000)
          p(style="font-size:0.7em;") "So far as the engines of history are concerned, meaning does not matter. In principle, one could study the history of a literary tradition without reading any of literature. ... the main virtue of the computerized content analysis methods I use is that they save one from actually having to read the literature" - Martindale
        section
          h2 "The Great Unread"
          ul
            li Thousands of books published in 19th century England
            li Only a few studied now by famous authors
            li Computational techniques can reveal trends
            ul
              li Titles became shorter
              li Text became less abstract
        section
          h4 Analysis methods for Distant Reading - Diachronic Frequency Analysis
          img(src="img/presidents_freq.png" width="65%")
          small Source: Figure 1.4.1 – The Atlantic’s “The Language of the State of the Union” © Benjamin Schmidt, Mitch Fraa, Chris Barna, Libby Bawcombe, Noah Gordon, Betsy Ebersole, Jennie Rothenberg Gritz 
        section
          h4 Analysis methods for Distant Reading - Lexical Diversity
          img(src="img/hip_hop_vocab.png" width="90%")
          small Source: Matt Daniels
        section
          h4 Analysis methods for Distant Reading - Topic Modelling
          img(src="img/topic_modelling.png")
        section
          h2 Narrative Analysis
          ul
            li Content (topics, characters, events, ...)
            li Structure (plot, character relationsships, ...)
            li Discourse (narrator, style, ...)
          p Approach: collect text, annotate, analyse
